{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 11:07:13.532215", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary of network health\\n- Server farm segment 10.200.0.0/24 is up and reachable from at least one user network (10.2.1.0/24). Core OSPF backbone and server access router appear operational for that path.\\n- User network 10.2.1.0/24 (host_2_1_1_1) has end-to-end connectivity: DNS resolution works and web access via the load balancer (web99.local) returns in ~1.0–1.1 s.\\n- User network 10.1.1.0/24 (host_1_1_1_1) is effectively isolated from the rest of the network: routing to central services is broken, causing DNS failures, HTTP failures, and DHCP lease non-renewal.\\n\\nDetected anomalies\\n1) OSPF adjacency missing between router_dist_1_1 and the core in area 0.0.0.1:\\n- router_dist_1_1 OSPF shows 0 neighbors on both br0 (10.1.1.1/24 area 0.0.0.1) and eth0 (172.16.0.7/31 area 0.0.0.1). Neighbor Count is 0 on each.\\n- router_core_1 OSPF shows no neighbor on eth2 (172.16.0.6/31) in area 0.0.0.1 (Neighbor Count is 0), while it has healthy adjacencies in the backbone (area 0.0.0.0) toward other cores.\\n\\n2) Missing OSPF reachability for 10.1.1.0/24 across the core/server plane:\\n- server_access_router OSPF routes:\\n  - Has O>* 10.2.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.10 (working).\\n  - Does not have a route to 10.1.1.0/24.\\n- router_core_1 OSPF routes show no learned route to 10.1.1.0/24 either.\\n\\n3) Host 10.1.1.0/24 loses DHCP lease and becomes unroutable:\\n- host_1_1_1_1 initially had 10.1.1.10/24 with “valid_lft 24sec” (very short lease).\\n- Shortly thereafter, ip -4 addr shows only loopback (lost the address), and all pings/curls return “Network is unreachable.”\\n- DHCP server config uses default-lease-time 30; max-lease-time 60. With the routing to the DHCP server broken at the distribution layer, the client’s T1/T2 renewals fail, leading to lease expiry and loss of the IP.\\n\\n4) DNS and HTTP behavior consistent with routing/DHCP issues on 10.1.1.0/24:\\n- host_1_1_1_1 resolv.conf points to 10.200.0.2 (dns_server) but cannot reach it; curl to web0.local..web3.local yields ~5.0 s totals (typical DNS timeout pattern) before the host completely loses its IP.\\n- host_2_1_1_1 resolv.conf is the same, but its curl to web0.local completes in ~1.0 s and to web99.local in ~1.0–1.13 s (healthy path).\\n\\nDetailed evidence\\n- Reachability snapshot:\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> dns_server: ICMP replies received with ~2.2 ms RTT; curl to web0.local returns in ~1.0–1.08 s; to web99.local in ~1.02–1.13 s.\\n  - host_1_1_1_1: pings to dns_server/load_balancer/servers return “Network is unreachable” after lease expiry; curl to names (web0.local..web3.local) shows ~5 s totals (DNS failures) before full unroutability.\\n- DHCP server configuration:\\n  - default-lease-time 30; max-lease-time 60; networks and options are correct (routers and DNS pointing to 10.1.1.1 and 10.200.0.2 respectively).\\n- OSPF status:\\n  - router_dist_1_1:\\n    - “show ip ospf interface” shows Area 0.0.0.1 on eth0 (172.16.0.7/31) and br0 (10.1.1.1/24) with Neighbor Count 0 on both.\\n    - “show ip route” contains only connected routes: 10.1.1.0/24 (br0) and 172.16.0.6/31 (eth0). No learned routes to server or other areas.\\n  - router_core_1:\\n    - ABR with areas 0.0.0.0 and 0.0.0.1; in area 0.0.0.1 (eth2 172.16.0.6/31) Neighbor Count 0.\\n    - No OSPF-learned route to 10.1.1.0/24; backbone and other links healthy (neighbors on eth0 and eth1).\\n  - server_access_router:\\n    - OSPF adjacency to core exists and routes to 10.2.1.0/24 present; route to 10.1.1.0/24 absent, confirming the 10.1.1 area is not being advertised/received by the server side.\\n\\nLocalization of the fault\\n- Fault domain: The link/OSPF adjacency between router_dist_1_1 (172.16.0.7/31) and router_core_1 (172.16.0.6/31) in area 0.0.0.1.\\n- Downstream effect: router_dist_1_1 does not learn routes to central services (10.200.0.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, etc.) and cannot relay packets to DNS/DHCP/servers. Consequently, hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 cannot reach central services; DHCP renew fails and hosts lose IP configuration.\\n- Unaffected domain: router_dist_2_1 path toward the core and servers is healthy; hosts in 10.2.1.0/24 work normally.\\n\\nRoot cause assessment\\n- The OSPF adjacency between router_dist_1_1 and router_core_1 in area 0.0.0.1 is down, isolating the 10.1.1.0/24 segment from the backbone and server farm. This breaks routing for DNS and DHCP renewals, and ultimately causes host_1_1_1_1 to lose its IP lease and become unroutable.\\n- The precise underlying reason for the failed adjacency is not visible from the collected data, but symptoms point to a control-plane adjacency failure on the 172.16.0.6/31–172.16.0.7/31 link (e.g., OSPF neighbor formation issue). Both sides show Network Type BROADCAST on a /31 and report 0 neighbors in area 0.0.0.1, while other adjacencies in the backbone are healthy.\\n\\nImpact\\n- 10.1.1.0/24 user network:\\n  - DNS unreachable, HTTP to web servers/LB fails.\\n  - DHCP renewals fail; clients lose IP addresses after very short lease times and become offline.\\n- 10.2.1.0/24 user network:\\n  - Fully functional: DNS, HTTP, and routing to server farm are healthy.\\n\\nNo remediation steps are proposed at this stage., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='1f09cc76-eebe-4566-b185-7c9db4cdcb86'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
